 Goddess and the Polis. Parthenon Project Japan 2011\u20132014'' Phoibos Verlag, Wien 2016, {{ISBN|978-3-85161-124-3}}.\n* {{cite book|last=Queyrel|first=Fran\u00e7ois|title=Le Parth\u00e9non: un monument dans l'histoire|year=2008|publisher=Bartillat|isbn=978-2-84100-435-5}}.\n* Papachatzis, Nikolaos D. ''Pausaniou Ellados Periegesis- Attika'' Athens, 1974.\n* Tournikio, Panayotis. ''Parthenon''. Abrams: 1996. {{ISBN|0-8109-6314-0}}.\n* Traulos, Ioannis N. '' I Poleodomike ekselikses ton Athinon'' Athens, 1960 {{ISBN|960-7254-01-5}}\n* Woodford, Susan. ''The Parthenon''. Cambridge University, 1981. {{ISBN|0-521-22629-5}}.\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons|Parthenon}}\n{{Wiktionary}}\n{{EB1911 Poster|Parthenon}}\n{{Library resources box |by=no |onlinebooks=yes |others=yes |about=yes |label=Parthenon\n  |viaf= |lcheading= |wikititle= }}\n* [http://odysseus.culture.gr/h/2/eh251.jsp?obj_id=912 The Acropolis of Athens: The Parthenon] (official site with a schedule of its opening hours, tickets and contact information)\n* [http://www.yppo.gr/4/e40.jsp?obj_id=123 (Hellenic Ministry of Culture) The Acropolis Restoration Project]\n* [http://www.parthenonfrieze.gr (Hellenic Ministry of Culture) The Parthenon Frieze] {{in lang|el}}\n* [https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/404 UNESCO World Heritage Centre \u2013 Acropolis, Athens]\n* [http://www.nashville.gov/parthenon/index.htm Metropolitan Government of Nashville and Davidson County \u2013 The Parthenon]\n* [http://www.metrum.org/key/athens/index.htm The Athenian Acropolis by Livio C. Stecchini] (Takes the heterodox view of the date of the proto-Parthenon, but a useful summary of the scholarship.)\n* [http://www.acropolisfriends.gr/index.php?lang=en The Friends of the Acropolis]\n* [http://people.hsc.edu/drjclassics/lectures/ParthenonMarbles/marbles.shtm Illustrated Parthenon Marbles] \u2013 Dr. Janice Siegel, Department of Classics, [[Hampden\u2013Sydney College]], Virginia\n* [http://travels.co.ua/engl/greece/athens/acropolis/parthenon/index.html Parthenon:description, photo album]\n* View a digital reconstruction of the Parthenon [https://sketchfab.com/models/4552d90409924583b1fadfc9953134cb in virtual reality from Sketchfab]\n\n===Videos===\n* [[:File:Athens Acropolis Parthenon day.ogg|A Wikimedia video of the main sights of the Athenian Acropolis]]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MLCW0zKR4xk ''Secrets of the Parthenon''] video by [[Public Broadcasting Service]], on YouTube\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aGitmYl6U90 ''Parthenon'' by Costas Gavras]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pyzTAG9V-_o The history of Acropolis and Parthenon from the Greek tv show ''\u0397 \u039c\u03b7\u03c7\u03b1\u03bd\u03ae \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a7\u03c1\u03cc\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5'' (''Time machine'')] {{in lang|el}}, on YouTube\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XN44e3jmDSA ''The Acropolis of Athens in ancient Greece \u2013 Dimensions and proportions of Parthenon'' on Youtube]\n* [https://video.ias.edu/amiaslecture-connelly Institute for Advanced Study: The Parthenon Sculptures]\n\n{{Acropolis of Athens}}\n{{Ancient Greece topics}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:438 BC]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in the 5th century BC]]\n[[Category:Temples of Athena]]\n[[Category:Acropolis of Athens]]\n[[Category:Ancient Greek buildings and structures in Athens]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Athens]]\n[[Category:Destroyed temples]]\n[[Category:Temples in ancient Athens]]\n[[Category:Sculptures by Phidias]]\n[[Category:Greek temples]]\n[[Category:Conversion of non-Christian religious buildings and structures into churches]]\n[[Category:Religious buildings and structures converted into mosques]]\n[[Category:Former mosques in Greece]]\n[[Category:Ruins in Greece]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Sites in Greece]]\n[[Category:Persecution of pagans in the late Roman Empire]]\n", "name_user": "Redskull123", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parthenon"}
{"title_page": "Tadhg Kennelly", "text_new": "{{Use Irish English|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox AFL biography\n| name = Tadhg Kennelly\n| image = Tadhg Kennelly 2018.2.jpg\n| caption = Kennelly playing in July 2018\n| fullname = Tadhg Kennelly\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1981|7|1}}\n| birth_place = [[Listowel]], [[County Kerry]], Ireland\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| originalteam = [[Kerry GAA|Kerry (underage)]]\n| height = 190 cm\n| weight = 90 kg\n| position = \n| statsend = 2011\n| club1 = {{AFL Syd}}\n| years1 = 2001\u201308; 2010\u201311\n| games_goals1 = 197 (30)\n| nationalyears1 = 2001\u20132011\n| nationalteam1 = [[Ireland international rules football team|Ireland]]\n| nationalgames_goals1 = 6\n| careerhighlights =\n*Sydney premiership player [[2005 AFL Grand Final|2005]]\n*[[2002 AFL Rising Star]] nominee Rd 19\n}}\n\n'''Tadhg Kennelly''' (born 1 July 1981) is an Irish sportsperson known for his top level careers in both [[Gaelic football]] and [[Australian rules football]]. He is the only holder of both an [[2005 AFL Grand Final|AFL Premiership medallion]] and a [[2009 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final|Senior All-Ireland Championship medal]], the highest possible achievement in both sports. He has also represented [[Ireland international rules football team|Ireland]] in the [[International Rules Series]].\n\nKennelly grew up playing Gaelic football with [http://listowelemmetsgaa.com/ Listowel Emmets] in Kerry, but moved to Australia to play professional [[Australian rules football]] in the [[Australian Football League]]. He is best known in Australia as the first Irish-born player to have received an AFL Premiership medallion and the first AFL player to represent Ireland against [[Australia international rules football team|Australia]] in the International Rules Series. After [[Jim Stynes]] he is the second most experienced player associated with the [[Irish experiment]].\n\nKennelly returned to his native Listowel to play in the [[2009 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship]]. On 20 September 2009, he started the [[2009 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final|All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final]] as part of Kerry's All-Ireland winning side, scoring two points during the game and thus becoming the first person to win an AFL Premiership and a Senior All-Ireland Championship. After achieving his dream, he returned to the AFL to play for Sydney, after missing one season.\n\n==Early life==\nKennelly was born in [[Listowel]] in 1981 to mother Nuala<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/afl/kennellys-champion-irish-dad-dies-after-being-there-for-tadhgsswans-fairytale/2005/12/07/1133829661245.html | work=The Sydney Morning Herald | title=Kennelly's champion Irish dad dies after being there for Tadhg's Swans fairytale | date=8 December 2005}}</ref> and father [[Tim Kennelly]], a former [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship]] winner with [[Kerry GAA]].<ref name=SMH_SydneySwansPremiership05_Kennellys_GAAChampionDadDies>{{cite news |author=Cowley, Michael |date=5 December 2005 |work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]] |title=Kennelly's champion Irish dad dies after being there for Tadhg's Swans fairytale |url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/afl/kennellys-champion-irish-dad-dies-after-being-there-for-tadhgsswans-fairytale/2005/12/07/1133829661245.html |accessdate=29 November 2008}}</ref>\n\nTadhg grew up playing Gaelic football and was recognised as a highly talented underage player with Kerry GAA.<ref>[http://www.breakingnews.ie/archives/2004/0326/sport/kfeyauauojid/ Kennelly to miss Swans' AFL opener | BreakingNews.ie<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He was scouted by a number of [[Football league|English]] [[soccer]] teams, including [[Tranmere Rovers]] and [[West Bromwich Albion|West Brom]], and had under-age trials for the [[Republic of ireland football team|Irish national team]] before being recruited by [[Blackburn Rovers]].<ref name=\"IrishmanAbroad\"/> Within a few months he decided to return to Ireland.<ref name=\"IrishmanAbroad\">{{cite podcast |url=https://soundcloud.com/an-irishman-abroad/tadhg-kennelly-episode-193 |first=Jarlath |accessdate=1 June 2017 |authorlink=Jarlath Regan |edition=193 |work=[[An Irishman Abroad]] |title=Tadhg Kennelly |publisher=[[SoundCloud]] |date=26 May 2017 |last=Regan}}</ref>\n\n==Sporting career==\n\n===Underage Gaelic football career===\nHe first played with the [[Kerry GAA|Kerry]] minor team in 1997 when he won a [[Munster Minor Football Championship]] overcoming [[Limerick GAA|Limerick]]. He was underage again in 1998 and won a second Munster title after another win over [[Limerick GAA|Limerick]]. He missed out on three in a row in 1999 as [[Cork GAA|Cork]] took the tilte.\n\nWhile still a minor he was part of the counties Under 21 team. He won a Munster title after over coming Cork in the final. A surprise loss in the All-Ireland final to [[Westmeath GAA|Westmeath]] was his lot. He made a return to the Under 21 team in 2002, lining out in the All-Ireland semi-final loss to [[Galway GAA|Galway]].\n\n===AFL career, 2001\u20132008===\nIn 1999, he signed a rookie contract with the Sydney Swans.<ref>[http://listowelemmets.kerry.gaa.ie/historyoftheclub.html Listowel Emmets<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080326191445/http://listowelemmets.kerry.gaa.ie/historyoftheclub.html |date=26 March 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.rte.ie/tv/ttv/thecafe/tadhgjoe.html/ RTE TV] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081005044630/http://www.rte.ie/tv/ttv/thecafe/tadhgjoe.html |date=5 October 2008 }}</ref>\nAfter his debut in 2001 (following elevation from the [[AFL Draft|rookie list]]), he became a permanent fixture in the Sydney line-up as a dashing rebound defender, wearing the number 17 [[Guernsey (clothing)#Use in Australian rules football|guernsey]].\n\nKennelly earned an [[AFL Rising Star]] nomination in round 19 of 2002, consolidating his reputation as an upcoming young talent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afl.com.au/News/NEWSARTICLE/tabid/208/Default.aspx?newsId%3D3412 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-01-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080723195039/http://www.afl.com.au/News/NEWSARTICLE/tabid/208/Default.aspx?newsId=3412 |archivedate=23 July 2008 }}</ref> He was second (behind [[Leo Barry]]) for [[rebound (sports)|rebound]]s (77) from the defensive [[50-metre arc]] in 2004.\n\nKennelly became the first [[Irishman]] to win an [[AFL Premiership]] medal in 2005, after playing all 26 games for the Sydney Swans that year. He was reportedly earning $750,000 (350,000 Euro), while playing for the Sydney Swans. The hype in Australia surrounding Kennelly's appearance in the [[2005 AFL Grand Final|AFL Grand Final]] was so much that [[Network Ten]] sent out its usual game-day [[boundary rider (sport)|boundary rider]], [[Andrew Maher]], over to [[County Kerry]] to visit Tadhg's family for the week and watch the Grand Final with them.  Kennelly also appeared in the 2006 Grand Final, but the Swans lost 85\u201384 to the [[West Coast Eagles]].<ref>http://www.breakingnews.ie/archives/2006/0930/sport/cwqlsnauauid/ BreakingNews.ie report</ref>\n\nIn 2007 and 2008 after several seasons missing only a handful of games, Kennelly suffered a series of serious leg and shoulder injuries which became major setbacks to his AFL career.  His knee buckled from a heavy tackle from the [[Melbourne Demons]]' [[Byron Pickett]], causing an [[anterior cruciate ligament]] tear and seeing him miss several matches and later matches due to complications.  In 2008, he again injured his knee, [[joint dislocation|dislocating]] his [[knee cap]] and injuring his shoulder. He was selected in the [[Dream Team Australian rules football team|Dream Team]] for the [[AFL Hall of Fame Tribute Match]],<ref>[http://www.worldfootynews.com/article.php/2008041512023030 Kennelly represents the world in AFL Tribute Match] from worldfootynews.com</ref> but later withdrew due to injury.  He was quick to recover, however, and made an appearance for the Swans the following week, though again succumbed to the injury curse. During the rest of 2008, Kennelly's shoulder continually dislocated during games and his unorthodox methods of popping it back in was the subject of much media interest.<ref>[https://archive.is/20121230085620/http://www.foxsports.com.au/story/0,8659,24327591-23211,00.html Swans draw on spirit of Kelly] By Jenny McAsey for FoxSports.com.au 11 September 2008]</ref>\n\nOn several occasions during his AFL career, Kennelly had expressed a desire to return home to Ireland and leave the AFL, as he would like to emulate the success of his father and win an [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship]] medal with his native county's team, [[Kerry GAA|Kerry]].<ref name=\"kerrygaa.ie\">[http://www.kerrygaa.ie/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=118&Itemid=2 Kerry GAA \u2013 Tadhg Kennelly to Return to Kerry Football<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\nIn December 2005, Kennelly's father [[Tim Kennelly|Tim]] died suddenly at age 51.<ref name=SMH_SydneySwansPremiership05_Kennellys_GAAChampionDadDies/> It is believed his father's death may have some bearing on Kennelly's wish to return to Ireland.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/afl/family-man-torn-between-home-and-blood-brothers/2006/09/09/1157222378362.html | work=The Sydney Morning Herald | title=Family man torn between home and blood brothers | date=10 September 2006}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 August 2006 Kennelly ended months of speculation by announcing he would be staying on with the Swans for a further three years. Kennelly said that this would be his last AFL contract and that he would be returning to Ireland at the end of the three-year contract.  In March 2008, Kennelly was reported to have announced that he would \"definitely\" return to Ireland in 2009<ref>http://www.kerryman.ie/news/kennelly-calls-time-on-aussie-rules-career-1594283.html</ref> to play with Kerry, saying \"I want to win an All-Ireland with Kerry.\"<ref name=\"kerrygaa.ie\"/><ref>[http://www.hoganstand.com/Kerry/ArticleForm.aspx?ID=91674 Hoganstand.com \u2013 GAA Football & Hurling<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Kennelly announced his return to Ireland and Gaelic football in January 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/irishexaminer/pages/story.aspx-qqqg=sport-qqqm=sport-qqqa=sport-qqqid=83158-qqqx=1.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-01-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605124255/http://www.irishexaminer.com/irishexaminer/pages/story.aspx-qqqg=sport-qqqm=sport-qqqa=sport-qqqid=83158-qqqx=1.asp |archivedate=5 June 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Gaelic football career 2009===\n{{Infobox Gaelic Athletic Association player\n| code             = Football\n| sport            = Gaelic football\n| image            = \n| name             = Tadhg Kennelly\n| irish            = Tadhg Mac an Fhail\u00ed\n| feet             = 6\n| inches           = 3\n| fullname         = \n| county           = Kerry\n| province         = Munster\n| club             = [[Listowel Emmets GAA|Listowel Emmets]]\n| clposition       = \n| clubs            = [[Listowel Emmets GAA|Listowel Emmets]]\n| clyears          = \n| clapps(points)   = 66APPS \n| clcounty         = \n| clprovince       = \n| clallireland     = \n| counties         = [[Kerry GAA|Kerry]]\n| icposition       = Half Forward\n| icyears          = 2009\n| icapps(points)   = 6 (0\u20138)\n| icprovince       = 0\n| icallireland     = 1 (2009)\n| icnationalleague = 1 (2009)\n| allstars         = 1\n| clupdate         = \n| icupdate         = November 2009\n| birth_place      = [[Listowel]], [[County Kerry]]\n}}\n\nUpon returning to Kerry, Kennelly was given a job as a coaching officer by the Kerry County Board.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/kennelly-to-take-up-coaching-role-1660229.html | work=Irish Independent | first=Colm | last=Keys | title=Kennelly to take up coaching role | date=4 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nHe played his first competitive game for the [[Kerry GAA|Kerry]] Senior team on 8 March 2009 when he came on as a substitute in the [[2009 National Football League (Ireland)|Irish NFL]] against [[Derry GAA|Derry]], and there was speculation that he would be a member of the Kerry squad for the [[2009 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|All-Ireland Senior Football Championship]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/different-strokes-as-gaa-clocks-adjust-to-summer-time-1665144.html | work=Irish Independent | title=Different strokes as GAA clocks adjust to summer time | date=8 March 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2009/0308/derry_kerry.html | work=RT\u00c9 News | title=Derry 0\u201310 Kerry 0\u201312 | date=8 March 2009 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090310120201/http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2009/0308/derry_kerry.html | archivedate=10 March 2009 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> He went on to win an [[National Football League (Ireland)|Irish NFL]] medal when Kerry defeated Derry in the final in [[Croke Park]].  As Kerry had a number of injuries meaning that [[Darragh \u00d3 S\u00e9]], [[Anthony Maher (footballer)|Anthony Maher]], [[S\u00e9amus Scanlon]] and [[Kieran Donaghy]] were all short of full fitness, Kennelly played in Kerry's first two games of the All-Ireland Senior Football Championship in June. He picked up an injury during the qualifier series but his form continued to improve and after an impressive appearance as a substitute in the All-Ireland quarter-final against [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]], he broke into the starting team for the semi-final in which Kerry beat [[Meath GAA|Meath]]. On 20 September 2009 he played the first 50 minutes of the [[2009 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final|All-Ireland final]] win against [[Cork GAA|Cork]], scoring 2 points and becoming the first person to win an AFL premiership and an All-Ireland Senior Football Championship.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2009/0920/kennellyt.html |title=Kennelly adds to family's medal haul |date=21 September 2009 |work=RT\u00c9 Sport |accessdate=21 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090924190714/http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2009/0920/kennellyt.html |archivedate=24 September 2009 }}</ref> After the final Kennelly committed himself to the Kerry football team for the 2010 season, despite speculation that he was returning to Australia.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2009/0922/kennellyt.html |title=Kennelly commits himself to Kerry |date=22 September 2009 |work=RT\u00c9 Sport |accessdate=22 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090923182253/http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2009/0922/kennellyt.html |archivedate=23 September 2009 }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2009 he published his autobiography, ''Unfinished Business'', [[ghost written]] with Scotty Gullen.<ref>{{Cite book| publisher = Mercier Press| isbn = 978-1-85635-639-8| last = Kennelly| first = Tadhg| title = Tadhg Kennelly : Unfinished Business| year = 2009}}</ref>\nThe book sparked controversy when a paragraph claimed that he setting out to make his mark at the start of the All-Ireland by deliberately colliding with [[Nicholas Murphy]]. After a big backlash, Kennelly released a statement where he stated he was taken out of context by his ghost writer.<ref>[http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/kennelly-is-an-admirable-sportsman-who-has-to-accept-his-own-mistakes-1923980.html Kennelly is an admirable sportsman who has to accept his own mistakes]</ref>\n\nIn November 2009, Kennelly informed the Kerry county board of his intention to return to the AFL in 2010.<ref>{{cite news| title = Tadhg Kennelly to return to AFL| publisher = [[RT\u00c9 Sport]]| accessdate = 7 November 2009| date = 6 November 2009| url = http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2009/1106/kennellyt.html| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20091109020810/http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2009/1106/kennellyt.html| archivedate = 9 November 2009| df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===AFL career, 2009\u20132010===\nOn 12 November 2009, Kennelly signed a two-year deal with the Sydney Swans, marking his return to the AFL. In addition to his playing role, he took up a coaching role at the club.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/rfnews/kennelly-returns-to-swans/2009/11/12/1257615129317.html |title=His body healed, Kennelly returns to Swans |work=[[The Age]] |date=12 November 2009 |access-date= |author= }}</ref> He was very consistent throughout the year playing in his customary role off half back. He was chosen in the Irish squad for the International Series in October.\n\nKennelly played his final AFL game in {{AFL Syd}}'s semi-final defeat to {{AFL Haw}} on 16 September 2011; having played 197 AFL games.\n\n==Statistics==\n:<ref>[http://afltables.com/afl/stats/players/T/Tadhg_Kennelly.html Tadhg Kennelly's player profile at AFL Tables]</ref>\n\n{{AFL player statistics legend}}\n\n{{AFL player statistics start}}\n|- style=\"background-color: #EAEAEA\"\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" | [[2001 AFL season|2001]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{AFL Syd}}\n| 41 || 8 || 3 || 1 || 36 || 13 || 49 || 11 || 5 || 0.4 || 0.1 || 4.5 || 1.6 || 6.1 || 1.4 || 0.6\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" | [[2002 AFL season|2002]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{AFL Syd}}\n| 17 || 20 || 7 || 3 || 127 || 100 || 227 || 46 || 26 || 0.4 || 0.2 || 6.4 || 5.0 || 11.4 || 2.3 || 1.3\n|- style=\"background:#eaeaea;\"\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" | [[2003 AFL season|2003]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{AFL Syd}}\n| 17 || 24 ||