ork=[[Screenonline]] |publisher=[[British Film Institute]] |location=London |accessdate=27 December 2011 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite web |url=https://www.dvdtalk.com/dvdsavant/s3601xper.html |title=The Quatermass Xperiment Review |first=Glenn |last=Erickson |authorlink=Glenn Erickson |year=2011 |work=DVD Savant |accessdate=3 January 2012 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite web |url=https://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/9589/quatermass-xperiment-the/ |title=The Quatermass Xperiment (Region 2) |first=Stuart |last=Galbraith IV |authorlink=Stuart Galbraith IV |year=2004 |work=DVD Talk |accessdate=3 January 2012 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6105578.stm |title=Quatermass creator dies, aged 84 |publisher=[[BBC News Online]] |date=1 November 2006 |accessdate=27 December 2011 |ref={{SfnRef|BBC News Online|1 November 2006}} }}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.hammerfilms.com/productions/film/filmid/106/the-quatermass-xperiment |title=The Quatermass Xperiment |year=2012 |work=Hammer Films |publisher=Exclusive Media Group |accessdate=4 February 2012 |ref={{SfnRef|Hammer Films|2012}} |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106162339/http://www.hammerfilms.com/productions/film/filmid/106/the-quatermass-xperiment |archivedate= 6 January 2012 }}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.soundtrackcollector.com/title/10084/Quatermass+Film+Music+Collection,+The |title=Quatermass Film Music Collection, The|year=2012 |work=Soundtrack Collector |accessdate=2 January 2012 |ref={{SfnRef|Soundtrack Collector|2012}} }}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|0049646}}\n* {{Amg movie|153617}}\n* {{tcmdb title|id=4909}}\n* {{AFI film|id=54179|title=The Creeping Unknown}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|the-quatermass-xperiment}}\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20120106162339/http://www.hammerfilms.com/productions/film/filmid/106/the-quatermass-xperiment The Quatermass Xperiment]'' at [[Hammer Film Productions|Hammer Films]]\n* ''[http://www.screenonline.org.uk/film/id/525280/index.html The Quatermass Xperiment]'' at the [[British Film Institute]]'s Screenonline\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20090804161719/http://geocities.com/TelevisionCity/8504/qe.htm The Quatermass Xperiment]'' at The Quatermass Home Page\n* [http://www.geocities.ws/jgclarke2000/quaterma.htm The Quatermass Trilogy \u2013 A Controlled Paranoia]\n* [http://www.quatermass.org.uk Quatermass.org.uk \u2013 Nigel Kneale & Quatermass Appreciation Site]\n* [http://trailersfromhell.com/creeping-unknown/ ''The Creeping Unknown''] at [[Trailers From Hell]]\n\n{{Quatermass}}\n{{Val Guest}}\n\n{{good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Quatermass Xperiment, The}}\n[[Category:1955 films]]\n[[Category:1950s science fiction films]]\n[[Category:1955 horror films]]\n[[Category:1950s monster movies]]\n[[Category:British science fiction films]]\n[[Category:British monster movies]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Val Guest]]\n[[Category:British black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films about astronauts]]\n[[Category:Films based on television series]]\n[[Category:Films set in London]]\n[[Category:Hammer Film Productions horror films]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into comics]]\n[[Category:Quatermass]]\n", "name_user": "Vokafone", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Quatermass_Xperiment"}
{"title_page": "Venezuelan patrol boat Naiguat\u00e1", "text_new": "[[File:Arbv GC23.jpg|thumb|''Naiguat\u00e1'' during sea trials]]\n'''''Naiguat\u00e1''''', pennant number GC-23, was a {{convert|79.9|m|adj=on}} littoral [[patrol boat]] of the Venezuelan Coast Guard.  BVL stands for \"Buque de Vigilancia de Litoral,\" which is Spanish for littoral surveillance ship. The vessel was constructed by [[Navantia]] in [[C\u00e1diz]], Spain beginning in 2008. On 30 March 2020, the vessel rammed the [[cruise ship]] {{ship||RCGS Resolute}} in international waters. ''Naiguat\u00e1'' sank and the cruise ship fled.\n\n==Construction and career==\n''Naiguat\u00e1'' was the third ship of the {{sclass-|Guaicamacuto|patrol boat|0}} BVLs.  BVL stands for \"Buque de Vigilancia de Litoral,\" which is Spanish for littoral [[Patrol boat|surveillance ship]]. It was built by [[Navantia]] in Spain at the San Fernando shipyards in [[C\u00e1diz]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=MIGUEL GONZ\u00c1LEZ |title=Espa\u00f1a retira su apoyo al buque de guerra 'Comandante Eterno Hugo Ch\u00e1vez' |url=https://elpais.com/internacional/2019/01/28/actualidad/1548699378_893143.html |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |date=29 January 2019 |language=es |quote=A diferencia de los siete anteriores, su construcci\u00f3n no se llev\u00f3 a cabo en los astilleros de San Fernando (C\u00e1diz), sino en los de Puerto Cabello, en el Estado de Carabobo (Venezuela)}}</ref> based on a standard Navantia Avante 1400 design.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.navantia.es/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Avante-1400.pdf|title=Wayback Machine|date=April 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403021835/https://www.navantia.es/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Avante-1400.pdf|archive-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.janes.com/article/95271/venezuelan-coast-guard-patrol-ship-sinks-following-collision|title=Venezuelan Coast Guard patrol ship sinks following collision &#124; Jane's 360|date=April 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403023806/https://www.janes.com/article/95271/venezuelan-coast-guard-patrol-ship-sinks-following-collision|archive-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>  Its keel was laid in October 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://www.mnve.mil.ve/web/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=99&Itemid=31|title =Puesta de quilla del Tercer Buque de Vigilancia Litoral| accessdate =25 June 2009|publisher =Misi\u00f3n Naval Venezolana en Espa\u00f1a|date =October 2008|language =es|doi =|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20090322172714/http://www.mnve.mil.ve/web/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=99&Itemid=31|archive-date =22 March 2009}}</ref>  The Venezuelan Navy took delivery of ''Naiguat\u00e1'' from the builder and subsequently transferred it to the Venezuelan Coast Guard Command.  Its weapons systems consisted of one Leonardo [[OTO Melara 76 mm]] gun, one [[Close-in weapon system|CIWS]] anti-aircraft/anti-missile [[Rheinmetall Oerlikon Millennium Gun]], and two 12.7 mm machine guns.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.infodefensa.com/latam/2020/02/26/noticia-chavez-sometido-quinta-prueba.html|archiveurl=http://archive.today/20200403025258/https://www.infodefensa.com/latam/2020/02/26/noticia-chavez-sometido-quinta-prueba.html|archive-date=3 April 2020 |url-status=dead|title=El BVL Hugo Ch\u00e1vez fue sometido a su quinta prueba de mar - Noticias Infodefensa Am\u00e9rica}}</ref>\n\n==Sinking==\n''Naiguat\u00e1'' sank following its purposeful ramming of the Portuguese cruise liner {{ship||RCGS Resolute}} while in international waters on 30 March 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/venezuelan-navy-ship-sinks-after-ramming-reinforced-cruise-liner-6t9wggf5d|title=Venezuelan navy ship sinks after ramming reinforced cruise liner|first=Stephen Gibbs|last=Venezuela|via=www.thetimes.co.uk}}</ref>  The President of Venezuela accused the captain of the cruise ship of \"terrorism,\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/04/02/venezuelan-naval-vessel-goes-confrontation-portuguese-cruise/|title=Venezuelan naval vessel goes down after confrontation with Portuguese cruise ship|first=James|last=Badcock|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=April 2, 2020|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> adding later that he did not rule out that ''RCGS Resolute'' was \"carrying mercenaries to attack onland military bases.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.curacaochronicle.com/post/main/venezuelan-president-ship-that-is-docked-in-curacao-carries-mercenaries-to-attack-venezuela/|title=Venezuelan President: Ship that is docked in Cura\u00e7ao carries mercenaries to attack Venezuela|website=www.curacaochronicle.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nieuwsbladtransport.nl/scheepvaart/2020/04/02/venezolaans-marineschip-naar-de-kelder-na-rammen-pool-cruiseschip/|title=Venezolaans marineschip naar de kelder na rammen pool-cruiseschip|website=Nieuwsblad Transport}}</ref>   The Venezuelan minister of defence said ''RCGS Resolute''{{'}}s action was an act of \"imperial aggression.\"  With ''Naiguat\u00e1'', Venezuela \"lost a third of its ''Guaicamacuto'' class patrol ship fleet.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/32853/this-venezuelan-patrol-ship-sunk-itself-after-ramming-a-cruise-liner-with-an-reinforced-hull|title=This Venezuelan Patrol Ship Sunk Itself After Ramming A Cruise Liner With A Reinforced Hull|first=Joseph|last=Trevithick|website=The Drive}}</ref> The magazine ''[[Popular Mechanics]]'' said \"an unarmed cruise ship that takes no aggressive action cannot be an aggressor and commit \"piracy\" against an armed navy patrol boat.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.popularmechanics.com/military/navy-ships/a32021287/venezuela-cruiser-cruise-ship-collide/|title=Naval Patrol Boat Takes on Cruise Ship. Loses Real Bad.|first=Kyle|last=Mizokami|date=April 2, 2020|website=Popular Mechanics}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Patrol vessels]]\n[[Category:Ships of the Bolivarian Navy of Venezuela]]\n[[Category:2011 ships]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 2020]]\n[[Category:Ships sunk in collisions]]\n[[Category:Shipwrecks in the Caribbean Sea]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Arbv GC23.jpg|thumb|''Naiguat\u00e1'' during sea trials]]\n'''''Naiguat\u00e1''''', pennant number GC-23, was a {{convert|79.9|m|adj=on}} littoral [[patrol boat]] of the Venezuelan Coast Guard.  BVL stands for \"Buque de Vigilancia de Litoral,\" which is Spanish for littoral surveillance ship. The vessel was constructed by [[Navantia]] in [[C\u00e1diz]], Spain beginning in 2008. On 30 March 2020, the vessel rammed the [[cruise ship]] {{ship||RCGS Resolute}} in international waters. ''''Naiguat\u00e1'' sank and the cruise ship fled.\n\n==Construction and career==\n''Naiguat\u00e1'' was the third ship of the {{sclass-|Guaicamacuto|patrol boat|0}} BVLs.  BVL stands for \"Buque de Vigilancia de Litoral,\" which is Spanish for littoral [[Patrol boat|surveillance ship]]. It was built by [[Navantia]] in Spain at the San Fernando shipyards in [[C\u00e1diz]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=MIGUEL GONZ\u00c1LEZ |title=Espa\u00f1a retira su apoyo al buque de guerra 'Comandante Eterno Hugo Ch\u00e1vez' |url=https://elpais.com/internacional/2019/01/28/actualidad/1548699378_893143.html |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |date=29 January 2019 |language=es |quote=A diferencia de los siete anteriores, su construcci\u00f3n no se llev\u00f3 a cabo en los astilleros de San Fernando (C\u00e1diz), sino en los de Puerto Cabello, en el Estado de Carabobo (Venezuela)}}</ref> based on a standard Navantia Avante 1400 design.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.navantia.es/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Avante-1400.pdf|title=Wayback Machine|date=April 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403021835/https://www.navantia.es/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Avante-1400.pdf|archive-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.janes.com/article/95271/venezuelan-coast-guard-patrol-ship-sinks-following-collision|title=Venezuelan Coast Guard patrol ship sinks following collision &#124; Jane's 360|date=April 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403023806/https://www.janes.com/article/95271/venezuelan-coast-guard-patrol-ship-sinks-following-collision|archive-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>  Its keel was laid in October 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url =http://www.mnve.mil.ve/web/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=99&Itemid=31|title =Puesta de quilla del Tercer Buque de Vigilancia Litoral| accessdate =25 June 2009|publisher =Misi\u00f3n Naval Venezolana en Espa\u00f1a|date =October 2008|language =es|doi =|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20090322172714/http://www.mnve.mil.ve/web/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=99&Itemid=31|archive-date =22 March 2009}}</ref>  The Venezuelan Navy took delivery of ''Naiguat\u00e1'' from the builder and subsequently transferred it to the Venezuelan Coast Guard Command.  Its weapons systems consisted of one Leonardo [[OTO Melara 76 mm]] gun, one [[Close-in weapon system|CIWS]] anti-aircraft/anti-missile [[Rheinmetall Oerlikon Millennium Gun]], and two 12.7 mm machine guns.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.infodefensa.com/latam/2020/02/26/noticia-chavez-sometido-quinta-prueba.html|archiveurl=http://archive.today/20200403025258/https://www.infodefensa.com/latam/2020/02/26/noticia-chavez-sometido-quinta-prueba.html|archive-date=3 April 2020 |url-status=dead|title=El BVL Hugo Ch\u00e1vez fue sometido a su quinta prueba de mar - Noticias Infodefensa Am\u00e9rica}}</ref>\n\n==Sinking==\n''Naiguat\u00e1'' sank following its purposeful ramming of the Portuguese cruise liner {{ship||RCGS Resolute}} while in international waters on 30 March 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/venezuelan-navy-ship-sinks-after-ramming-reinforced-cruise-liner-6t9wggf5d|title=Venezuelan navy ship sinks after ramming reinforced cruise liner|first=Stephen Gibbs|last=Venezuela|via=www.thetimes.co.uk}}</ref>  The President of Venezuela accused the captain of the cruise ship of \"terrorism,\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/04/02/venezuelan-naval-vessel-goes-confrontation-portuguese-cruise/|title=Venezuelan naval vessel goes down after confrontation with Portuguese cruise ship|first=James|last=Badcock|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=April 2, 2020|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> adding later that he did not rule out that ''RCGS Resolute'' was \"carrying mercenaries to attack onland military bases.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.curacaochronicle.com/post/main/venezuelan-president-ship-that-is-docked-in-curacao-carries-mercenaries-to-attack-venezuela/|title=Venezuelan President: Ship that is docked in Cura\u00e7ao carries mercenaries to attack Venezuela|website=www.curacaochronicle.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nieuwsbladtransport.nl/scheepvaart/2020/04/02/venezolaans-marineschip-naar-de-kelder-na-rammen-pool-cruiseschip/|title=Venezolaans marineschip naar de kelder na rammen pool-cruiseschip|website=Nieuwsblad Transport}}</ref>   The Venezuelan minister of defence said ''RCGS Resolute''{{'}}s action was an act of \"imperial aggression.\"  With ''Naiguat\u00e1'', Venezuela \"lost a third of its ''Guaicamacuto'' class patrol ship fleet.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/32853/this-venezuelan-patrol-ship-sunk-itself-after-ramming-a-cruise-liner-with-an-reinforced-hull|title=This Venezuelan Patrol Ship Sunk Itself After Ramming A Cruise Liner With A Reinforced Hull|first=Joseph|last=Trevithick|website=The Drive}}</ref> The magazine ''[[Popular Mechanics]]'' said \"an unarmed cruise ship that takes no aggressive action cannot be an aggressor and commit \"piracy\" against an armed navy patrol boat.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.popularmechanics.com/military/navy-ships/a32021287/venezuela-cruiser-cruise-ship-collide/|title=Naval Patrol Boat Takes on Cruise Ship. Loses Real Bad.|first=Kyle|last=Mizokami|date=April 2, 2020|website=Popular Mechanics}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Patrol vessels]]\n[[Category:Ships of the Bolivarian Navy of Venezuela]]\n[[Category:2011 ships]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 2020]]\n[[Category:Ships sunk in collisions]]\n[[Category:Shipwrecks in the Caribbean Sea]]\n", "name_user": "RetiredDuke", "label": "safe", "comment": "''", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Venezuelan_patrol_boat_Naiguat%C3%A1"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States", "text_new": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|2=Talk:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States#Requested move 3 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{short description|Viral outbreak in the United States}}\n{{pp-move-indef|small=yes}}\n{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{short description|none}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=February 2020}}\n<!--NOTE: Please discuss on talk page before putting a \"current event\" template here. This is intended for short-term use only per advice at Template:Current-->\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States\n| map1            = COVID-19 outbreak USA per capita cases map.svg\n| legend1         = Confirmed cases per million residents\n| disease         = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = United States\n| first_case      = [[Everett, Washington]]<!--no source, not mentioned in the article-->\n| arrival_date    = January 15, 2020<ref name= NEJMFirstCase/><br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=15|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}} ago)\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sheikh |first1=Knvul |last2=Rabin |first2=Roni Caryn |title=The Coronavirus: What Scientists Have Learned So Far |url=https://www.nytimes.com/article/what-is-coronavirus.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 10, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n| deaths          = 5,758 ([[Johns Hopkins University|JHU]])<ref name=\"JHU\">{{cite web| last = Johns Hopkins CSSE| title = Coronavirus COVID19 (2019-nCoV)| work = Coronavirus COVID-19 Global Cases| format = ArcGIS| accessdate = April 2, 2020| url = https://www.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6}}</ref><br /> 4,513 ([[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] confirmed)<ref name=\"CDC_case_numbers\">{{cite news |title=Cases in U.S. |url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/cases-updates/cases-in-us.html |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |agency=Center for Disease Control}}</ref>\n| confirmed_cases = 244,678 ([[Johns Hopkins University|JHU]])<ref name=\"JHU\"/><br /> 213,144 ([[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] confirmed)<ref name=\"CDC_case_numbers\"/>\n| recovery_cases  = 9,058 ([[Johns Hopkins University|JHU]])<ref name=\"JHU\"/>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://coronavirus.gov/}}\n}}{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=January 2020}}An ongoing [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|worldwide pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] ({{nowrap|COVID-19}}), a new infectious disease caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] ({{nowrap|SARS-CoV-2}}), was first confirmed to have spread to the [[United States]] in January 2020. Cases have been confirmed in all fifty [[U.S. state]]s, the [[Washington, D.C.|District of Columbia]], and all inhabited [[Territories of the United States|U.S. territories]] except [[American Samoa]].<ref name=\"mariana\">{{cite web|url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/03/28/saipan-confirms-two-covid-19-positive-cases/2932326001/|title=Saipan confirms two COVID-19 positive cases|date=March 28, 2020|website=www.samoanews.com|language=en|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> {{As of|2020|03|31|df=US}}, the U.S. has the most confirmed active cases in the world and ranks third in the number of total deaths from the virus.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=https://gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6|title=Coronavirus COVID-19 Global Cases by the Center for Systems Science and Engineering (CSSE) at Johns Hopkins |access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe first known case of {{nowrap|COVID-19}} in the U.S. was confirmed on January 20, 2020, in a 35-year-old man who had returned from [[Wuhan]], China, five days earlier.<ref name=NEJMFirstCase>{{cite journal |vauthors=Holshue ML, DeBolt C, Lindquist S, Lofy KH, et al |title=First Case of 2019 Novel Coronavirus in the United States |journal=N. Engl. J. Med. |volume=382 |issue=10 |pages=929\u2013936 |date=March 2020 |pmid=32004427 |doi=10.1056/NEJMoa2001191 }}</ref> The [[White House Coronavirus Task Force]] was established on January 29.<ref name=\"Jan29WH\">{{cite press release|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/statement-press-secretary-regarding-presidents-coronavirus-task-force/|date=January 29, 2020|accessdate=March 15, 2020|publisher=[[White House]]|title=Statement from the Press Secretary Regarding the President's Coronavirus Task Force}}</ref> Two days later, the [[Presidency of Donald Trump|Trump administration]] declared a [[public health emergency (United States)|public health emergency]] and announced restrictions on travelers arriving from China.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2020/01/31/801686524/trump-declares-coronavirus-a-public-health-emergency-and-restricts-travel-from-c |work= [[NPR]] |date= January 31, 2020 |accessdate= March 18, 2020 |title= Trump Declares Coronavirus A Public Health Emergency And Restricts Travel From China |author= Aubrey, Allison}}</ref> On February 26, the first case in the U.S. in a person with \"no known exposure to the virus through travel or close contact with a known infected individual\" was confirmed by the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) in northern California.<ref name=HomeGrown>{{cite news |url= https://www.sacbee.com/news/california/article240674471.html |work= [[The Sacramento Bee]] | title= First U.S. coronavirus case of unknown origin confirmed in Northern California, CDC says |author= Smith, Darrell and Cathie Anderson |date= February 26, 2020 |accessdate= March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe United States got off to a slow start in [[COVID-19 testing]].<ref name=WhoriskeyMarch16/><ref name=WangMarch22/><ref>{{Cite news|last=Pilkington|first=Ed|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/mar/28/trump-coronavirus-politics-us-health-disaster|title=The missing six weeks: how Trump failed the biggest test of his life|date=March 28, 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=March 28, 2020|last2=McCarthy|first2=Tom|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Until the end of February, the [[Food and Drug Administration|Food and Drug Administration (FDA)]] procedures forbade laboratories other than the CDC from releasing test results to patients, even if they followed internationally recognized test protocols. The CDC developed and distributed test kits of its own, but many of them were found to have a manufacturing flaw in a non-essential component, which made the kit illegal to use until the protocol was changed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/cdc-coronavirus-testing-error-resolved-by-throwing-away-reagent-2020-3|title=For more than 2 weeks, state labs were told they couldn't use the CDC's coronavirus tests\u2014but the tests could have been used all along|first=Aria|last=Bendix|website=Business Insider|date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref name=WhoriskeyMarch16/><ref name=WangMarch22/> On February 29 the FDA began allowing public health agencies, hospitals, and private companies to develop tests and perform testing, and by mid-March private companies were shipping hundreds of thousands of tests.<ref name=LeeMarch21/> The FDA initially had very restrictive guidelines on who was allowed to be tested; on March{{nbsp}}5 it said anyone with a doctor's order could be tested.<ref name=WangMarch22/> As of March 25, at least 418,000 tests had been conducted,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Subramaniam |first1=Tara |last2=Lybrand |first2=Holmes |title=Fact Check: US has done more coronavirus tests than South Korea, but not per person |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/25/politics/coronavirus-testing-trump-south-korea-fact-check/index.html |website=CNN}}</ref> and by April 2 the number had reached 1,280,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/interactives/2020/coronavirus-testing-by-state-chart-of-new-cases/|title=Live tracker: How many coronavirus cases have been reported in each U.S. state?|last=Jin|first=Beatrice|date=March 30, 2020|work=Politico|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe CDC warned that widespread transmission of the disease may force large numbers of people to seek hospitalization and other healthcare, which may overload healthcare systems.<ref name=\"CDC COVID-19 Situation Summary\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/summary.html |title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) Situation Summary |last=CDC |publisher=CDC |accessdate=March 7, 2020|date=March 7, 2020 }}</ref> Since March 19, 2020, the U.S. [[United States Department of State|Department of State]] has advised U.S. citizens to avoid all international travel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://travel.state.gov/content/travel/en/traveladvisories/ea/travel-advisory-alert-global-level-4-health-advisory-issue.html|title=Global Level 4 Health Advisory\u2014Do Not Travel|website=travel.state.gov}}</ref> On March 16 the White House advised against any gatherings of more than 10 people.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Liptak |first1=Kevin |title=White House advises public to avoid groups of more than 10, asks people to stay away from bars and restaurants |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/16/politics/white-house-guidelines-coronavirus/index.html |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=[[CNN]] |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> In mid-March 2020, the [[Federal Emergency Management Agency]] (FEMA) told the [[United States Army Corps of Engineers]] (USACE) to plan to construct new facilities, including leased hotels and other buildings, and to convert them for use as [[hospitals]] and [[intensive care unit]]s.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.enr.com/articles/48927-rep-defazio-fema-asks-army-corps-to-help-build-emergency-health-facilities|title=Rep. DeFazio: FEMA Asks Army Corps to Help Build Emergency Health Facilities|last1=Ichniowski|first1=Tom|last2=Rubin|first2=Debra K.|date=March 18, 2020|work=Engineering News-Record|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/balajis/status/1242029099310133248|title=Ok. It's just one clip. But it's by far the most intelligent thing I've heard any government official say in the last few months. Further increases likelihood the military will take over COVID19 response in the near future. |website=twitter.com/usarmy|first=Balaji S.|last=Srinivasan|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> [[U.S. state and local government response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic|State and local responses]] to the outbreak have included prohibitions and cancellation of large-scale gatherings, the closure of schools and other educational institutions, the cancellation of [[trade fair|trade shows]], [[Convention (meeting)|conventions]], and [[music festival]]s, and the cancellation and suspension of [[Sport|sporting events]] and [[Sports league|leagues]].<ref name=\"nyt sports\">{{Cite news|last=Deb|first=Sopan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/11/sports/basketball/warriors-coronavirus-fans.html|title=Sports Leagues Bar Fans and Cancel Games Amid Coronavirus Outbreak|date=March 11, 2020|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=March 12, 2020|last2=Cacciola|first2=Scott|issn=0362-4331|last3=Stein|first3=Marc}}</ref>\n\n==Current number of non-repatriated cases by states and territories==\n\n<div style=\"display: flex; width: 100%;\"><!--serious rendering issues in current article with it floated to the right-->{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States cases by state}}</div>\n\nThe CDC publishes official numbers every Monday, Wednesday, and Friday, reporting several categories of cases: individual travelers, people who contracted the disease from other people within the U.S., and repatriated citizens who returned to the U.S. from crisis locations, such as [[Wuhan]], where the disease originated, and the cruise ship ''Diamond Princess''.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/cases-in-us.html|title=International Locations with Confirmed COVID-19 Cases|date=February 11, 2020|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222072600/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/cases-in-us.html|archive-date=February 22, 2020|access-date=February 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n\n{{gallery\n| File:COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in the United States (Density).svg|Map of states and territories in the U.S. with number of confirmed cases ({{As of|2020|04|01|lc=y|df=US}})\n{{legend|#D3D3D3|None confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FFDDCC|<500 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FFAAAA|500\u2013999 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FF7777|1,000\u20131,999 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FF0000|2,000\u20134,999 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#BB0000|5,000\u201350,000 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#500000|>50,000 confirmed}}\n| File:COVID-19 Pandemic Deaths in the United States (Density).svg|Map of states and territories in the U.S. with number of confirmed deaths ({{As of|2020|3|31|lc=y|df=US}})\n{{legend|#D3D3D3|None confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FFDDCC|1\u20134 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FFAAAA|5\u20139 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FF7777|10\u201349 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FF0000|50\u201399 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#BB0000|100\u2013500 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#500000|>500 confirmed}}\n| File:COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in the United States by counties (Confirmed).svg|Confirmed COVID-19 cases by county ({{As of|2020|04|01|lc=y|df=US}})\n| File:Lab-specimens-tested.jpg|Number of tests done per day in the United States by the CDC and public health labs (private labs are not included)<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) |url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/testing-in-us.html |website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention |accessdate=March 10, 2020 |date=February 11, 2020}}</ref>{{br}}\u00a7 Data during this period are pending.\n| File:CoViD-19 US.svg|Number of cases (blue) and number of deaths (red) on a [[logarithmic scale]]\n|title=}}\n\nThe following numbers are based on CDC data. However, CDC data is incomplete. In most U.S. locations, testing for some time was performed only on symptomatic people with a history of travel to Wuhan or with close contact to such people.<ref name=\"Madrigal\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/925233|title=Persons Evaluated for 2019 Novel Coronavirus\u2014US, Jan 2020|website=Medscape|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/new-york-man-denied-coronavirus-test-japan-trip-fever-cough-2020-3|title=A New York City man wasn't tested for the coronavirus even though he had symptoms and had gone to Japan. It highlights the troublingly limited scope of US testing.|first=Morgan|last=McFall-Johnsen|website=Business Insider|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> A quarantined nurse in California, showing symptoms of COVID-19 but without a travel history, said she was denied testing by the CDC in early March.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2020/03/08/u-s-response-to-the-covid-19-coronavirus-moves-from-containment-to-mitigation|title=US response to the COVID-19 coronavirus moves from 'containment' to 'mitigation'|date=March 8, 2020|first=Jonathan|last=Shieber|work=TechCrunch}}</ref> CDC testing protocols did not include non-travelling patients with no known contact with China until February 28.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/27/health/us-cases-coronavirus-community-transmission/index.html|title=The CDC has changed its criteria for testing patients for coronavirus after the first case of unknown origin was confirmed|first1=Sarah |last1=Moon |first2=Holly |last2=Yan |first3=Jen |last3=Christensen |first4=Christina|last4=Maxouris|publisher=CNN|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe original CDC-developed tests sent out on February{{nbsp}}5 turned out to be faulty.<ref name=\"factcheck.org\">{{cite web|url=https://www.factcheck.org/2020/03/trumps-misplaced-blame-on-obama-for-coronavirus-tests/|title=Trump's Misplaced Blame on Obama for Coronavirus Tests|first=Jessica|last=McDonald|date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> On February 29, the FDA announced that labs would be allowed to do their own in-house testing immediately, independently of CDC testing, as long as they complete an emergency use authorization (EUA) within 15 days.<ref name=\"factcheck.org\"/> In Washington, state regulators at one point told health care workers to stop testing previously collected samples from an existing non-COVID19 flu study.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/10/world/coronavirus-news.html|title=U.S. Cases of Coronavirus Surpass 1,000; British Health Minister Is Infected|date=March 10, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020|work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nAs of March 18, the CDC reported that 37,824 specimens had been tested for COVID-19, 4,484 of which were tested by CDC labs, and 33,340 tested by U.S. public health labs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/cases-updates/testing-in-us.html|title=Testing in the U.S.|last=|first=|date=March 16, 2020|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316204847/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/cases-updates/testing-in-us.html|archive-date=March 16, 2020|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation estimates a peak in deaths per day by April 15, with a total of about 80,000 deaths in the United States due to coronavirus by August.<ref>{{cite web|website=The Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation (IHME)|url=https://covid19.healthdata.org/projections|title=COVID-19 Projections|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n===CDC reported U.S. totals===\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States medical cases chart}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Cases in the United States per the CDC<ref>{{cite web |title=Cases in the US |url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/cases-updates/cases-in-us.html |website=CDC.gov |publisher=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref><br>As of April 1, 2020\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"| Cases in the United States reported to CDC\n|-\n|Travel-related || style=\"text-align:right\"|1,110\n|-\n|Close contact|| style=\"text-align:right\" |3,128\n|-\n|Under investigation ||style=\"text-align:right\" |181,863\n|-\n!Total cases !!style=\"text-align:right\" |186,101\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\"|\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Cases among persons repatriated to the United States\n|-\n|Wuhan, China||style=\"text-align:right\"|3\n|-\n| Cruise ship [[Diamond Princess outbreak|''Diamond Princess'']] || style=\"text-align:right\" |46\n|-\n!Total repatriated cases!! style=\"text-align:right\" |49\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\"|\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"| Deaths\n|-\n!Total deaths from all U.S. cases!! style=\"text-align:right\" |3,603<ref name=\"CDC_case_numbers\"/>\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |This table reflects CDC-published totals, and may not include cases announced in the past 24 hours.\n|}\n{{clear}}\n\n===State number of non-repatriated cases by date {{anchor|State number of reported cases by date}}===\n\n{{main|Template:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States medical cases}}\n<!-- Template for Graph:Chart is at [[Template:Graph:Chart]] -->\n\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type=line\n|linewidth=1\n|showSymbols=1\n|width=600\n|height=400\n|colors=#FF4343\n|showValues=\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|yAxisTitle=No. of cases\n|legend=Legend\n<!-- PLease clipboard copy the \"}x=...\" and \"y1=...\" lines from the log plot of total cases when you update these charts -->\n\n<!-- Search string CASES_X -->\n|x= Feb 26, Feb 27, Feb 28, Feb 29, Mar 1, Mar 2, Mar 3